{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28c14dec6ffei2yhPyO5TGMEeN","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d73eb35ba001srdS0JRZ3R4OfW","parts":[{"id":"prt_d73eb487d001gRoKAswfR99oUk","messageID":"msg_d73eb35ba001srdS0JRZ3R4OfW","sessionID":"ses_28c14dec6ffei2yhPyO5TGMEeN","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_581c48f05eaf40c4b322661a","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.rst"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.rst</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: ============\n2: Tortoise ORM\n3: ============\n4: \n5: .. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/tortoise-orm.svg?style=flat\n6:    :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/tortoise-orm\n7: .. image:: https://pepy.tech/badge/tortoise-orm/month\n8:    :target: https://pepy.tech/project/tortoise-orm\n9: .. image:: https://github.com/tortoise/tortoise-orm/workflows/gh-pages/badge.svg\n10:    :target: https://github.com/tortoise/tortoise-orm/actions?query=workflow:gh-pages\n11: .. image:: https://github.com/tortoise/tortoise-orm/actions/workflows/ci.yml/badge.svg?branch=develop\n12:    :target: https://github.com/tortoise/tortoise-orm/actions?query=workflow:ci\n13: .. image:: https://coveralls.io/repos/github/tortoise/tortoise-orm/badge.svg\n14:    :target: https://coveralls.io/github/tortoise/tortoise-orm\n15: \n16: Introduction\n17: ============\n18: \n19: Tortoise ORM is an easy-to-use ``asyncio`` ORM *(Object Relational Mapper)* inspired by Django.\n20: \n21: You can find the docs at `Documentation <https://tortoise.github.io>`_\n22: \n23: Tortoise ORM supports CPython 3.10 and later for SQLite, MySQL, PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, and Oracle.\n24: \n25: Why was Tortoise ORM built?\n26: ---------------------------\n27: \n28: Tortoise ORM was built to provide a lightweight, async-native Object-Relational Mapper for Python with a familiar Django-like API.\n29: \n30: Tortoise ORM performs well when compared to other Python ORMs. Here are `our benchmarks <https://github.com/tortoise/orm-benchmarks>`_ on PostgreSQL 17, where we measure different read and write operations (rows/sec, more is better):\n31: \n32: .. image:: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tortoise/tortoise-orm/develop/docs/ORM_Perf.png\n33:     :target: https://github.com/tortoise/orm-benchmarks\n34: \n35: How is an ORM useful?\n36: ---------------------\n37: \n38: An Object-Relational Mapper (ORM) abstracts database interactions, allowing developers to work with databases using high-level, object-oriented code instead of raw SQL.\n39: \n40: * Reduces boilerplate SQL, allowing faster development with cleaner, more readable code.\n41: * Helps prevent SQL injection by using parameterized queries.\n42: * Centralized schema and relationship definitions make code easier to manage and modify.\n43: * Handles schema changes through version-controlled migrations.\n44: \n45: Getting Started\n46: ===============\n47: \n48: Installation\n49: ------------\n50: \n51: The following table shows the available installation options for different databases (note that there are multiple options of clients for some databases):\n52: \n53: .. list-table:: Available Installation Options\n54:    :header-rows: 1\n55:    :widths: 30 70\n56: \n57:    * - Database\n58:      - Installation Command\n59:    * - SQLite\n60:      - ``pip install tortoise-orm``\n61:    * - PostgreSQL (psycopg)\n62:      - ``pip install tortoise-orm[psycopg]``\n63:    * - PostgreSQL (asyncpg)\n64:      - ``pip install tortoise-orm[asyncpg]``\n65:    * - MySQL (aiomysql)\n66:      - ``pip install tortoise-orm[aiomysql]``\n67:    * - MySQL (asyncmy)\n68:      - ``pip install tortoise-orm[asyncmy]``\n69:    * - MS SQL\n70:      - ``pip install tortoise-orm[asyncodbc]``\n71:    * - Oracle\n72:      - ``pip install tortoise-orm[asyncodbc]``\n73: \n74: \n75: Quick Tutorial\n76: --------------\n77: \n78: Define the models by inheriting from ``tortoise.models.Model``.\n79: \n80: \n81: .. code-block:: python3\n82: \n83:     from tortoise.models import Model\n84:     from tortoise import fields\n85: \n86:     class Tournament(Model):\n87:         id = fields.IntField(primary_key=True)\n88:         name = fields.CharField(max_length=20)\n89: \n90: \n91:     class Event(Model):\n92:         id = fields.BigIntField(primary_key=True)\n93:         name = fields.TextField()\n94:         tournament = fields.ForeignKeyField('models.Tournament', related_name='events', on_delete=fields.OnDelete.CASCADE)\n95:         participants = fields.ManyToManyField('models.Team', related_name='events', through='event_team', on_delete=fields.OnDelete.SET_NULL)\n96: \n97: \n98:     class Team(Model):\n99:         id = fields.UUIDField(primary_key=True)\n100:         name = fields.CharField(max_length=20, unique=True)\n101: \n102: \n103: After defining the models, Tortoise ORM needs to be initialized to establish the relationships between models and connect to the database.\n104: The code below creates a connection to a SQLite DB database with the ``aiosqlite`` client. ``generate_schema`` sets up schema on an empty database.\n105: ``generate_schema`` is for development purposes only; use the built-in\n106: migrations for production use.\n107: \n108: .. code-block:: python3\n109: \n110:     from tortoise import Tortoise, run_async\n111: \n112:     async def init():\n113:         # Here we connect to a SQLite DB file.\n114:         # also specify the app name of \"models\"\n115:         # which contain models from \"app.models\"\n116:         await Tortoise.init(\n117:             db_url='sqlite://db.sqlite3',\n118:             modules={'models': ['app.models']}\n119:         )\n120:         # Generate the schema\n121:         await Tortoise.generate_schemas()\n122: \n123:     run_async(main())\n124: \n125: ``run_async`` is a helper function to run simple Tortoise scripts. Check out `Documentation <https://tortoise.github.io>`_ for FastAPI, Sanic and other integrations.\n126: \n127: With the Tortoise initialized, the models are available for use:\n128: \n129: .. code-block:: python3\n130: \n131:     async def main():\n132:         await Tortoise.init(\n133:             db_url='sqlite://db.sqlite3',\n134:             modules={'models': ['app.models']}\n135:         )\n136:         await Tortoise.generate_schemas()\n137: \n138:         # Creating an instance with .save()\n139:         tournament = Tournament(name='New Tournament')\n140:         await tournament.save()\n141: \n142:         # Or with .create()\n143:         await Event.create(name='Without participants', tournament=tournament)\n144:         event = await Event.create(name='Test', tournament=tournament)\n145:         participants = []\n146:         for i in range(2):\n147:             team = await Team.create(name='Team {}'.format(i + 1))\n148:             participants.append(team)\n149: \n150:         # One to Many (ForeignKey) relations support creating related objects\n151:         another_event = await tournament.events.create(name='Another Event')\n152: \n153:         # Many to Many Relationship management is quite straightforward\n154:         # (there are .remove(...) and .clear() too)\n155:         await event.participants.add(*participants)\n156: \n157:         # Iterate over related entities with the async context manager\n158:         async for team in event.participants:\n159:             print(team.name)\n160: \n161:         # The related entities are cached and can be iterated in the synchronous way afterwards\n162:         for team in event.participants:\n163:             pass\n164: \n165:         # Use prefetch_related to fetch related objects\n166:         selected_events = await Event.filter(\n167:             participants=participants[0].id\n168:         ).prefetch_related('participants', 'tournament')\n169:         for event in selected_events:\n170:             print(event.tournament.name)\n171:             print([t.name for t in event.participants])\n172: \n173:         # Prefetch multiple levels of related entities\n174:         await Team.all().prefetch_related('events__tournament')\n175: \n176:         # Filter and order by related models too\n177:         await Tournament.filter(\n178:             events__name__in=['Test', 'Prod']\n179:         ).order_by('-events__participants__name').distinct()\n180: \n181:     run_async(main())\n182: \n183: \n184: Learn more at the `documentation site <https://tortoise.github.io>`_\n185: \n186: \n187: Migrations\n188: ==========\n189: \n190: Tortoise ORM ships with a built-in migration framework and CLI.\n191: Autodetect model changes, generate migration files, and apply them:\n192: \n193: .. code-block:: shell\n194: \n195:     tortoise init                # create migration packages\n196:     tortoise makemigrations      # detect changes and generate migrations\n197:     tortoise migrate             # apply pending migrations\n198:     tortoise sqlmigrate app 001  # preview SQL without executing\n199: \n200: Migrations support ``RunPython`` and ``RunSQL`` for data migrations, offline migration generation,\n201: reversible operations, and multi-app and multi db-schema projects.\n202: \n203: See the `migrations documentation <https://tortoise.github.io/migration.html>`_ for\n204: full setup and examples.\n205: \n206: Contributing\n207: ============\n208: \n209: Please have a look at the `Contribution Guide <docs/CONTRIBUTING.rst>`_.\n210: \n211: License\n212: =======\n213: \n214: This project is licensed under the Apache License - see the `LICENSE.txt <LICENSE.txt>`_ file for details.\n\n(End of file - total 214 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"============\nTortoise ORM\n============\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/tortoise-orm.svg?style=flat\n   :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/tortoise-orm\n.. image:: https://pepy.tech/badge/tortoise-orm/month\n   :target: https://pepy.tech/project/tortoise-orm\n.. image:: https://github.com/tortoise/tortoise-orm/workflows/gh-pages/badge.svg\n   :target: https://github.com/tortoise/tortoise-orm/actions?query=workflow:gh-pages\n.. image:: https://github.com/tortoise/tortoise-orm/actions/workflows/ci.yml/badge.svg?branch=develop\n   :target: https://github.com/tortoise/tortoise-orm/actions?query=workflow:ci\n.. image:: https://coveralls.io/repos/github/tortoise/tortoise-orm/badge.svg\n   :target: https://coveralls.io/github/tortoise/tortoise-orm\n\nIntroduction\n============\n\nTortoise ORM is an easy-to-use ``asyncio`` ORM *(Object Relational Mapper)* inspired by Django.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.rst","time":{"start":1775766292894,"end":1775766292900}}}]}
